feed.title: Changing the Guard
feed.transport: Victoria, Green Park, St Jamess Park, Hyde Park Corner
feed.station: Victoria, Green Park, St Jamess Park, Hyde Park Corner
feed.description:
Changing the Guard at Buckingham Palace encompasses colourful spectacle and British pageantry. During the Changing the Guard ceremony, also known as Guard Mounting, one regiment takes over from another. The Queens Guard is made up of the St Jamess Palace and Buckingham Palace detachments. The New Guard, who during the course of the ceremony become The Queens Guard, march to Buckingham Palace from Wellington Barracks with musical accompaniment.

Check website for confirmed dates and times.
feed.shortDescription: Changing the Guard at Buckingham Palace encompasses colourful spectacle and British pageantry.

feed.title: Lumiere Festival
feed.description: Lumiere is the UKs largest light festival. The festival, produced by London-based creative company Artichoke, debuted in Durham in 2009. The festival was part inspired by the Fete des lumieres in Lyon. Hosted in winter time, and free to attend, the festival typically comprises a number of light art installations, as well as illuminating iconic buildings and locations. The festival takes place biennially in November in Durham, and since 2013 has occasionally toured to other locations, both reusing popular illuminations from Durham and creating new bespoke installations. Check website for all the viewing locations.

feed.title: Southbank Centre Winter Festival
feed.description: Celebrate the winter season at the South Bank centre with festive shows and a christmas market at the Winter Festival at South Bank.

feed.title: Skate at Somerset House
feed.description: Londons most beautiful ice rink returns, transforming the Edmond J. Safra Fountain Court into a winter oasis, and ushering in the festive season with a 40ft Christmas tree. One of Londons favourite winter traditions, Skate at Somerset House with Fortnum and Mason has something for everybody, with skating lessons, our late night DJs series Skate Lates, and our first-ever Skate all-nighter on Saturday 07 December.

feed.title: Tower of London Ice Rink
feed.description: Located in the dry moat, the Tower of London ice rink offers a grand historical setting for seasonal skating sessions, along with views of London's ancient fortress and the river Thames.

feed.title: Natural History Museum Ice Rink
feed.description: Set against the backdrop of the Waterhouse building, the Ice Rink at the Natural History Museum is one of the most magical places to be this winter. Experience the thrill of skating surrounded by fairy lights nestled in frost-covered trees, with the smell of mulled wine in the air.

feed.title: Hampton Court Palace Ice Rink
feed.description: Skate around Henry VIII's sixteenth-century pad this festive season. Hampton Court Palace makes a mighty picturesque backdrop for this outdoor rink, especially when lit up after dark. The rink, which is right in front of the Tudor pile and by the side of the Thames, is an impressive 1,040 square metres. With sessions for beginners and experts, as well as food and drink pop-ups, this wintery attraction is ideal for skaters of all ages and skills. Wrap up warm and take a turn on the ice in this regal back yard.

feed.title: Alexandra Palace Ice Rink
feed.description: Ice skating can be enjoyed all year round at Alexandra Palace ice rink. Situated inside our iconic Victorian building this stunning location provides a backdrop like no other. Take a spin around the ice with family and friends, dance on ice, take up professional lessons, or even watch an ice hockey game. If youre looking for something a bit different, every month Londons top pop DJs Club De Fromage take over the ice rink for nostalgic ice disco sessions.
